Let $a_1, a_2, ...$ be a sequence of nonnegative real numbers and let $pi,
rho$ be permutations of the positive integers $NN$ (thus $pi, rho :
NN -> NN$ are one-to-one and onto maps).

Suppose that $display(sum_(n=1)^(infinity) a_n = 1)$ and $epsilon$ is
a real number such that

$ sum_(n=1)^(infinity) |a_n - a_(pi n)| + sum_(n=1)^(infinity) |a_n - a_(rho n)| < epsilon. $

Prove that there exists a finite subset $X$ of $NN$ such that $|X sect
pi X|, |X sect rho X| > (1 - epsilon)|X|$ (here $|X|$ indicates the
number of elements in $X$; also the inequalities $<, >$ are strict).
